The Latin phrase "Amor Fati" translates to "Love of Fate."  Friedrich
Nietzche (1844-1900) used the phrase in his work, "The Gay Science":

"I still live, I still think: I still have to live, for I still have to think.
Sum, ergo cogito: cogito, ergo sum. Today everybody permits
himself the expression of his wish and his dearest thought; hence
I, too, shall say what it is that I wish from myself today, and what
was the first thought to run across my heart this year--what
thought shall be for me the reason, warranty, and sweetness of my
life henceforth. I want to learn more and more to see as beautiful
what is necessary in things; then I shall be one of those who make
things beautiful. Amor Fati: let that be my love henceforth! I do not
want to wage war against that is ugly. I do not want to accuse; I
do not even want to accuse those who accuse. Looking away shall
be my only negation. And all in all and on the whole: some day I wish
to be only a Yes-sayer."

-o-o-o-o-o-o-o-o-o-o-o-o-o-o-o-o-o-o-o-o-o-o-o-o-o-o-o-o-o-o-

