The thread titled "Longevity" has over the last week or so has described
in great detail how evolution has *not* selected for longevity above all
else.  Creatures such as mice have evolved to trade individual longevity
off against other features which promote reproduction.   And humans have
been known to make great sacrifices, including longevity sacrifices, in
order to help their children prosper.  People do not buy the safest
possible car, or avoid driving except in emergencies; they clearly trade
off the risk of death against other things they value.  So do animals.
Advanced creatures who think of colonies as their children should be
willing to make great sacrifices to help them.

> > You seem to want to allow these creatures to place a small value on
