Rob misunderstands here.  Let me try to clear it up.  In Objectivist
discourse, there are three general classes of ethics (and of epistemology,
esthetics, politics, of evaluative disciplines in general).   These are:

1) Intrinsicist which place the good in the object.  Examples include the
Decalogue (Ten Commandments), which are _roughly_ a set of rules which are
taken to be good in themselves -- not because of what they do.

2) Subjectivist which place the good in the subject.  Examples include
people who say what is good is whatever they feel like calling good.

3) Objectivist which place the good in the relation of object to subject.
Within Rand's particular theory that relation which defines the good is that
which promotes (in a totalistic way) the agent's life.

> >I would quibble with one thing here which relates to my second point
above.
> >Morality, as such, need not be the same for each species or type of
being.
